<font color="#FF0000">CLOSURE </font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 25  2:10:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art,<br>
Sounds like you've spent some time in East LA. Felt many times like what you described after working the night shift in the City of the Angel's. Full of demons it was. <br>
Problem was, that it was real and thank God for pursuits that allowed the adrenaline to run. Perhaps that's why I was so reckless in those pursuits, chasing the dream, catching the demon, laughing and drinking until the morning light. <br><br>
I have never sought closure about Vietnam, didn't think I needed it, until I saw Rahm again.<br><br>
Rahm was the Marine that pried my hands off the M60 after the barrel melted on May 30, 1968. Funny he had been there all along but I hadn't seen him for months.<br><br>
I had not seen him since November. In November we lost a lot of men and Rahm was innocent then, he was care free and pleasant to be around. But when I saw him again in May, he had aged, he was no longer young, his smile was gone, he was a combat warrior who killed people, brown and green colored people with funny moon shaped hats. People that smiled when they died, full of heroin and laughter, and full of holes. Full of many many holes, small holes, large holes, funny shaped holes, people without bones. Bright colored leafs dripping wet in crimson gold. Hiding in the shadows of woes, smelling dirty, like piss and blood and sweat and guts and wet earth. Teeth glistering in the night, a gold cap tooth and small black plastic burying bags. <br>
Wow, that was funny, the gooks carried their own black body bags in their backpacks. So that their comrades would do them the honor of placing them in the bag and piling little small mounds of dirt over them. Buried with honor, and we left them there. The armtracks track wheels just went over them and mixed it all together and we moved on. <br>
Closure, only when I saw Rahm and we hugged and kissed and held our hands together, it was, it was, then, that I saw Rahm again. Young and full of laughter, joy and fulfillment. Full of cancer, and what, what does he say to me, he said, he said to me, I'll get my new leg soon and he leaned on me as we picked up his baggage together.<br><br>
Then when he was able to leave, we sat there at the airport waiting together, and I was so tired. We hugged and the people might had though us strange. But if they only knew the precious cargo, what a great warrior, father, friend and human being was to be traveling with them that night, they would have all bowed in respect and honor, but it was our secret and they would never understand, never appreciate who Rahm was. <br>
Then he said to me, go home now.<br>
Thank you, thank you for getting us all together. This, has been my dream for thirty years I had dreamed about this time, and now I am so grateful, now I can tell my wife and my children that I am at peace and I can die. <br>
Closure<br>

<p><code>-- 1st platoon, India 3/7, 1st Marine Division  June 1967-68   (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


